{Welcome to my course My First Opening Repetoire: Scandinavian Defence! My name is Alex Colovic and I'm a Grandmaster. I am the first Grandmaster on Chessable, having been a regular author on the platform since its beginning.  I have had some successes as a player and coach, but my biggest ones have been on Chessable, consistently creating best-selling courses. I have also become famous for my simplified approach to openings and in this course I will present you with one of the simplest openings for Black - the Scandinavian Defence. e4 is 'Best by test' as Bobby Fischer described the move with the king's pawn. This move is considered the most aggressive one for White because it opens the diagonals for both the light-squared bishop and the queen, seeking quick development of the pieces. With d5 , the move of the queen's pawn, Black immediately attacks White's undefended pawn on e4 . This move characterises the Scandinavian Defence (also known as the Centre Counter) .  The first known example of the Scandinavian Defence dates back to the 15th century and it has remained a popular opening choice ever since then. It has been used by many strong players, including former World Champions Magnus Carlsen, Vladimir Kramnik, and Vishwanathan Anand (who famously used it in his World Championship match against Garry Kasparov in 1995 and obtained a superior position) . Other top players like Nakamura and Caruana have also used the Scandinavian with great results.  Magnus Carlsen in particular has beaten many world-class Grandmasters with the Scandinavian, but perhaps the most famous game played in the Scandinavian was the televised game Bill Gates vs. Magnus Carlsen, played on 23 January 2014 as part of a Norwegian talk show. In that game, the then World Champion mated his famous opponent in only 9 moves! You will find that game in the chapter Third Move Alternatives . The main allure of the Scandinavian Defence is that it gives Black a very safe position without the danger of suffering a quick mate in an obscure gambit line.  Additionally, after the exchange of pawns and the queen excursion, which help establish an impregnable pawn formation, Black's play follows the basic opening concepts of rapid development and central control, something beginners must learn if they want to play openings well.  In the Scandinavian Black is guaranteed a strong pawn formation and smooth development in a position without weaknesses. This position, exd5 Qxd5 , arises after the exchange of the e4 and d5 -pawns when Black wants to play ... c6 and develop the light-squared bishop to f5 (or sometimes g4 ) before following up with ... e6 (the pawn formation of pawns on c6 and e6 without a pawn on d5 is known as 'the saw') , thus avoiding a passive bishop on c8 . After this, Black's development is almost automatic, with the following moves being played in one order or another: ... Nf6 , ... Be7 , ... Nbd7 , and ... O-O . Once Black obtains this set-up, they are guaranteed a safe and bullet-proof position.  The Scandinavian is a solid and straight-forward opening that perfectly suits the needs of a beginner who wishes to obtain a playable middlegame position without fear of suffering an early set-back due to lack of opening knowledge. This allows the beginner to focus on solid principles rather than navigating complex theoretical lines.  Furthermore, the middlegame positions that arise are uniform and consistent, which make them susceptible to concrete plans, which you will find outlined in the theoretical section.  This connection of the opening and the middlegame will ensure that the student knows how to play the middlegame and will always be able to discover opportunities in the positions that will arise. Because of this knowledge, beginners can play the Scandinavian with a certain degree of confidence, knowing that they won't be tricked in the opening and that they will know their way in the middlegame.  This beginner-friendly opening has surprise value while the knowledge of 'the saw' structure and the middlegame plans usually prove decisive in practice. As a bonus, the Scandinavian can be learned very quickly and can be played for a lifetime. Good luck with your studies and may all your opponents end up like Bill Gates in his game with Magnus Carlsen!} 1. Z0 *

