{In the Scandinavian Defence White's best move is to capture the pawn on d5 on move two. But even though the exchange of the pawns on d5 is the best move for White, some players will play other moves, hoping for a surprise. These moves are not very good ones and this chapter will equip you with everything you need to know about how to deal with these alternatives.} 1. e4 d5 {By playing ... d5 Black attacks the pawn on e4 . In this chapter, we will explore the alternatives to White's main move, exd5 , which is covered in detail in the next two chapters, ( chapter 2 and chapter 3 ) .} 2. d3 {This is a passive move that defends the pawn on e4 . Black has a choice, to take on e4 and enter a pleasant endgame or to take space in the centre by advancing the e-pawn.} e5 ({Black takes central control. The endgame that arises after the exchange of pawns on e4 after} 2... dxe4 3. dxe4 Qxd1+ 4. Kxd1 e5 {is very good for Black because White has lost the right to castle and Black has easy development with ... Nf6 and ... Bc5 next.}) 3. exd5 ({White's capture on d5 is the most commonly-played move. Attacking the pawn on e5 with} 3. Nf3 {is met by} Nc6 {, safely defending the pawn on e5 . Attacking the pawn on d5 with} 4. Nc3 {is met by} d4 {when play will resemble the line arising after Nc3 d4} 5. Ne2 {e5 .}) 3... Qxd5 {Black already has a development advantage thanks to the centralised queen.} 4. Nc3 ({Similar to the main line after exd5 Qxd5} 4. Nc3 {White attacks the queen, but in this case thanks to the e -pawn being already on e5 , Black has the option to keep the queen in the centre and continue development at the same time.}) 4... Bb4 ({This is the good move that Black can play thanks to the move e5 . The bishop pins the knight on c3 , thus White cannot capture the black queen on d5 . Black plans to continue development with moves like ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , or ... Nge7 and ... O-O , which will give them a very harmonious position. It's important to note that if White unpins the knight on c3 by playing Bd2 then Black simply drops the queen all the way back to d8 with} 4... Qd8 {(in the same way as in the main lines after exd5 Qxd5 Nc3 Qd8 ) and continues with the same developing moves outlined above.}) *

