{In the Scandinavian Defence White's best move is to capture the pawn on d5 on move two. But even though the exchange of the pawns on d5 is the best move for White, some players will play other moves, hoping for a surprise. These moves are not very good ones and this chapter will equip you with everything you need to know about how to deal with these alternatives.} 1. e4 d5 {By playing ... d5 Black attacks the pawn on e4 . In this chapter, we will explore the alternatives to White's main move, exd5 , which is covered in detail in the next two chapters, ( chapter 2 and chapter 3 ) .} 2. Nf3 {The knight move is a developing one, but it leaves the e4 -pawn without defence. Black should take the pawn.} dxe4 {Apart from being a pawn up, Black also attacks the knight on f3 .} 3. Ng5 {White attacks the pawn on e4 .} Bf5 ({Black defends the pawn on e4 and after ... Nf6 and ... e6 Black will have a solid position with an extra pawn. It's important to note that in the case of} 3... Nf6 {, which also defends the pawn on e4 (and is the usually recommended development advice of 'knights before bishops' ), White can play} 4. Bc4 {, attacking the pawn on f7 , which would force Black to play} e6 {and shut the light-squared bishop on c8 . In the Scandinavian, Black wants to avoid a bishop on c8 limited by a pawn on e6 . This is achieved with the recommended move Bf5 (an exception to the rule of thumb 'knights before bishops' ) because now in the case of Bc4 e6 the bishop is much more active on f5 .}) *

