{In the Scandinavian Defence White's best move is to capture the pawn on d5 on move two. But even though the exchange of the pawns on d5 is the best move for White, some players will play other moves, hoping for a surprise. These moves are not very good ones and this chapter will equip you with everything you need to know about how to deal with these alternatives.} 1. e4 d5 {By playing ... d5 Black attacks the pawn on e4 . In this chapter, we will explore the alternatives to White's main move, exd5 , which is covered in detail in the next two chapters, ( chapter 2 and chapter 3 ) .} 2. Qf3 {White develops the queen prematurely, going against the general advice to develop the light pieces first. On the other hand, the queen does defend the pawn on e4 and attacks the pawn on d5 at the same time.} dxe4 {Black avoids the attack on the pawn on d5 by capturing on e4 and attacking the white queen.} 3. Qxe4 {White recaptures the pawn, but now their queen is exposed in the centre as Black can gain time for development by attacking it.} Nf6 {Here it comes - Black develops and harasses the exposed white queen.} 4. Qf3 {White moves the queen again to avoid its capture.} e5 {Black advances with the e-pawn and grabs central space. This gives Black an advantage in development and their next moves will be ... Nc6 , ... Bd6 , and ... O-O , with a very harmonious position with excellent central control.} *

