{In the Scandinavian Defence White's best move is to capture the pawn on d5 on move two. But even though the exchange of the pawns on d5 is the best move for White, some players will play other moves, hoping for a surprise. These moves are not very good ones and this chapter will equip you with everything you need to know about how to deal with these alternatives.} 1. e4 d5 {By playing ... d5 Black attacks the pawn on e4 . In this chapter, we will explore the alternatives to White's main move, exd5 , which is covered in detail in the next two chapters, ( chapter 2 and chapter 3 ) .} 2. d4 {This move is a pawn sacrifice as the pawn on e4 is left without defence.} dxe4 {Black naturally takes the free pawn.} 3. Nc3 {White develops the knight and attacks the pawn on e4 .} Bf5 ({Black develops the light-squared bishop and defends the pawn on e4 . In the case of} 3... Nf6 4. Bg5 {White introduces the idea of Bxf6 , doubling the black pawns on the f-file after Black recaptures. With the bishop already on f5 , Black now wants to play ... Nf6 and ... e6 , with further ... Be7 and ... O-O .}) 4. f3 {White plays in gambit-style, sacrificing a pawn for development. They want to lure Black into capturing on f3 , when after Nxf3 or Qxf3 White would have a development advantage.} Nf6 {Black prefers not to give White what they want. By developing the knight Black defends the pawn on e4 and continues the development. They intend ... e6 and ... Be7 next, followed by ... O-O .  Once the king is safe (or on its way to safety), Black may consider taking on f3 as then their position would be extremely solid and White won't have ways to take advantage of the activity of their pieces.} *

