{In the Scandinavian Defence White's best move is to capture the pawn on d5 on move two. But even though the exchange of the pawns on d5 is the best move for White, some players will play other moves, hoping for a surprise. These moves are not very good ones and this chapter will equip you with everything you need to know about how to deal with these alternatives.} 1. e4 d5 {By playing ... d5 Black attacks the pawn on e4 . In this chapter, we will explore the alternatives to White's main move, exd5 , which is covered in detail in the next two chapters, ( chapter 2 and chapter 3 ) .} 2. Nc3 {By developing the knight White defends the attacked pawn on e4 and attacks Black's pawn on d5 . However, the knight only invites Black's space-grabbing next move.} d4 ({Black obtains a space advantage in the centre by attacking the knight and plans to build up the strong pawn centre with ... e5 . Taking on e4 would justify White's move as after} 2... dxe4 3. Nxe4 {the knight is nicely centralised.}) 3. Nce2 ({The knight retreats to a safe square and is en route to g3 . In the case of} 3. Nd5 $2 c6 4. Nf4 e5 5. Nd3 Bd6 {the knight gets kicked around and only helps Black's development, who will continue with ... c5 , ... Nc6 , ... Nge7 , just like in the line after Nce2 .}) 3... e5 {With simple and attacking moves Black obtained a strong pawn centre and a central space advantage, which can further be used for natural development.} 4. Ng3 ({White must play a third move with this hapless knight in order to allow for the development of the light-squared bishop, which would like to be developed on c4 . With this in mind, Black's next move is easily understandable. If White decides to shut his bishop with} 4. d3 $6 {then Black continues with natural development with} c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {and the further moves remains the same: ... Bd6 , ... Nge7 , ... f6 , ... Be6 just like after} 6. Ng3 {.}) 4... Be6 {Black develops the light-squared bishop and at the same time prevents the development of White's light-squared bishop on c4 .} 5. Nf3 {White continues development and attacks the pawn on e5 .} f6 {Black solidifies the centre. Their plan of the further development is ... c5 , ... Nc6 , ... Bd6 , ... Nge7 when Black can decide whether to castle queenside and attack on the kingside or castle on the kingside and attack on the queenside.  On the other hand, White has problems with the development of the bishop on f1 , at the same time suffering from lack of space.} *

