{In the Scandinavian Defence White's best move is to capture the pawn on d5 on move two. But even though the exchange of the pawns on d5 is the best move for White, some players will play other moves, hoping for a surprise. These moves are not very good ones and this chapter will equip you with everything you need to know about how to deal with these alternatives.} 1. e4 d5 {By playing ... d5 Black attacks the pawn on e4 . In this chapter, we will explore the alternatives to White's main move, exd5 , which is covered in detail in the next two chapters, ( chapter 2 and chapter 3 ) .} 2. e5 {This move is the most common alternative to the capture on d5 . White advances in the centre and hopes to avoid Black's preparation after exd5 . Some lesser alternatives are worth mentioning, if only not to be surprised by them and to know what to do.} Bf5 {Black develops the light-squared bishop before continuing with ... e6 , so as not to have it passive on c8 . This theme of development of the light-squared bishop before playing ... e6 is central to the whole opening.} 3. d4 {White expands in the centre and connects their pawns.} e6 {Black also strengthens their central structure and opens the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop on f8 . The plan of development is to play ... c5 and ... Nc6 , both of which attack White's pawn on d4 .} 4. Nf3 {White develops the kingside.} c5 {Black continues with the plan described in the previous move. Their intention is to play ... Nc6 and ... Qb6 with an easy play on the queenside and in the centre. This is demonstrated by the pressure that both the knight on c6 , the queen on b6 , and the pawn on c5 put on White's pawn on d4 .  White will find it hard to defend the pawn on d4 , especially if later on Black continues with ... Bg4 (attacking the knight on f3 that defends the pawn on d4 ) and ... Nge7 - f5 , adding another piece to the attack on the d4 -pawn.} ({A sample line on how the game can continue is c3} 4... Nc6 5. Bd3 {seeking the exchange of the active black bishop.} Bg4 $1 {this idea was mentioned earlier in the comment - Black pins the knight on f3 with the idea to capture it and eliminate a defender of the d4 -pawn. With} 6. Be2 {White attempts to break the pin on the knight on f3 , However, after} Bxf3 {Black consistently follows the plan. Now that a defender of the pawn on d4 is eliminated} 7. Bxf3 {cxd4 fixes the pawn on d4 , which means that now White cannot play dxc5 and exchange the vulnerable pawn. And all of a sudden, cxd4 Qb6 , Black wins a pawn - the pawn on d4 is attacked twice and the only way for White to defend it is by playing Be3 , but that leaves the pawn on b2 without defence, which means that Black will take it with Qxb2 . Black then has a safe extra pawn and a very solid position, with the further development of ... Nge7-f5 , ... Be7 , and ... O-O .}) *

