{In this chapter we begin our analysis of the best move for White, exd5 . After Black recaptures with the queen we will explore the alternatives to the main line with Nc3 , which is covered in the next chapter.  When White doesn't play Nc3 the most ambitious plan is to play for an advance with both central pawns by d4 and c4 . That plan is analysed as the main line in this chapter.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 {This is White's best move. White takes the pawn and forces Black to react to this capture.} Qxd5 {Black recaptures the pawn and centralises the queen. In this chapter we will take a look at the alternatives to White's most natural move Nc3 , which is covered in the chapter The Main Line with Nc3 .} 3. d4 ({This central advance has the same idea as} 3. Nf3 {. It will likely lead to a transposition to the same positions after...}) 3... c6 {Black plays the move ... c6 to control the d5 -square. This is particularly important when White plays d4 and c4 because with the support of the c4 -pawn White may threaten a further advance with d5 .  The move ... c6 is the first step on the way of the establishment of 'the saw' after ... e6 (after the development of the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4 , of course).} 4. c4 {White continues with the plan and attacks the black queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The retreat to d8 is typical for our repertoire. Whenever attacked the queen drops back to d8 where it is safe from any attacks.} 5. Nc3 ({White develops the queenside. In the case of} 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Nc3 e6 {we will have the same type of position as in the lines analysed after Nf3 c6 d4 Bg4} 7. Be2 {e6 c4 Qd8 .}) 5... Nf6 {Black develops the kingside. The idea of the move is to wait for White to develop the king's knight to f3 when the black light-squared bishop can be developed to g4 to pin it. After the light-squared bishop is developed, Black can proceed with ... e6 , thus establishing 'the saw' pawn construction.} 6. Nf3 {Natural development for White, following the general advice of 'knights before bishops' .} Bg4 {Black develops the bishop to the active g4 -square, pinning the knight on f3 . The immediate threat is to take the knight on f3 , when after Qxf3 Black will win a pawn by taking the pawn on d4 by ... Qxd4 . White is better advised to avoid that threat.} 7. Be2 {Now in case of ... Bxf3 White can recapture with a bishop and the queen stays on d1 to guard the d4 -pawn.} e6 ({Black successfully established 'the saw'. Now we have the same position as in the main line after Nf3 (after Black's 7th move} 7... Z0 {Nf6 ) and it is analysed via that move order.}) *

