{In this chapter we begin our analysis of the best move for White, exd5 . After Black recaptures with the queen we will explore the alternatives to the main line with Nc3 , which is covered in the next chapter.  When White doesn't play Nc3 the most ambitious plan is to play for an advance with both central pawns by d4 and c4 . That plan is analysed as the main line in this chapter.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 {This is White's best move. White takes the pawn and forces Black to react to this capture.} Qxd5 {Black recaptures the pawn and centralises the queen. In this chapter we will take a look at the alternatives to White's most natural move Nc3 , which is covered in the chapter The Main Line with Nc3 .} 3. c4 {The immediate attack on the queen before playing d4 is not very good.} Qe4+ {A very important disruptive check. White is already in trouble.} 4. Qe2 ({This cover from the check is the only one not to lose a pawn. In the case of} 4. Be2 $2 Qxg2 {Black wins the pawn on g2 , while after Ne2? Qxc4 Black wins the pawn on c4 . Now White threatens to pick up the queen on e4 in case Black forgets about it.}) 4... Qxe2+ {It's better not to forget about the hanging queen on e4 . By exchanging the queens Black forces White to recapture, thus winning time to continue with development.} 5. Bxe2 ({White wants to continue with d4 now, but Black's next developing move prevents it. In case of} 5. Nxe2 Nc6 {Black has two ideas:  a) To play ... e5 , obtaining a firm grip of the central d4 -square,  b) and ... Nb4 , threatening to win the rook on a1 thanks to the fork ... Nc2 .}) 5... Nc6 {Black develops the knight and controls the important central d4 -square, thus preventing White's central expansion with d4 .} 6. Nf3 {White develops the knight and wants to finally push d4 , thanks to the control of that square by the knight on f3 .} e5 {Black's central advance is directly aimed at preventing White's advance with d4 . In this position, Black's next moves will be ... Bf5 and ... O-O-O , which will put tremendous pressure on White's position on the d-file:  - The rook on d8 will control the d4 and d3 -squares.  - The bishop on f5 will control the d3 -square.  - The knight on c6 already controls the d4 -square, but it can also go to b4 to control the d3 -square.  This means that White has serious problems finishing development of the queenside, since moving the d2 -pawn to d3 , in order to open the c1 - h6 diagonal for the bishop on c1 , will be impossible because of Black's superior control of that square.} *

