{In this chapter we begin our analysis of the best move for White, exd5 . After Black recaptures with the queen we will explore the alternatives to the main line with Nc3 , which is covered in the next chapter.  When White doesn't play Nc3 the most ambitious plan is to play for an advance with both central pawns by d4 and c4 . That plan is analysed as the main line in this chapter.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 {This is White's best move. White takes the pawn and forces Black to react to this capture.} Qxd5 {Black recaptures the pawn and centralises the queen. In this chapter we will take a look at the alternatives to White's most natural move Nc3 , which is covered in the chapter The Main Line with Nc3 .} 3. Qf3 {White seeks an exchange of queens. It's a simplistic way of playing, but perhaps White enjoys playing endgames?} Qd8 {Black can oblige and obtain an equal endgame by exchanging queens (if they also like endgames), or they can retreat the queen to d8 , like in the other lines of the Scandinavian Defence, with the idea to take advantage of the exposed position of the white queen. This will be done by playing ... Nc6 , when the knight will threaten ... Nd4 or ... Ne5 , in both cases attacking the queen on f3 .} 4. Bc4 {White develops the bishop to an active square, attacking the pawn on f7 . Coupled with the queen's attack on that same pawn, White threatens an unpleasant Qxf7 .} Nf6 {Black develops the knight and block's the f-file, thus defending against the queen's attack on the pawn on f7 .} 5. Ne2 {White develops the king's knight and plans to castle. Another idea of the development of the knight is to push d4 , since now the knight controls that square and would support the pawn landing there.} Nc6 {An important move for Black. It's a developing move, but more importantly, it's a move that is dealing with White's threat of d4 , by establishing control over that square.  Now both the knight on c6 and the queen on d8 control the d4 -square, so a white pawn landing there would simply be captured for free.  However, the knight move also creates a threat of its own. The threat is the move ... Ne5 , which would be a double attack on the queen on f3 and the bishop on c4 . Black would gladly exchange the knight for the active bishop on c4 , as that would give them the advantage of the bishop pair, a long-term advantage that gives better long-term prospects to its possessor.} 6. Bb3 {White wisely avoids the double attack with ... Ne5 by removing the bishop from the vulnerable position.} e5 {Black uses the time that White spent on their last move to expand in the centre. Now the d4 -square is controlled three times (by the pawn on e5 , the knight on c6 , and the queen on d8 ), which means that White cannot liberate their play by pushing d4 .  Black's next moves will be ... Bd6 and ... O-O , which would complete the development of the kingside and ensure a safe haven for the black king. Further on, Black can consider the move ... Bg4 , harassing the exposed white queen on f3 .} *

