{Black castles and will follow up with ... Nbd7 next, achieving the ideal development set-up. Then they will try to use the ideas from the plans described in the comments to Black's 11th move in the main line after Re1 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 {This is White's best move. White takes the pawn and forces Black to react to this capture.} Qxd5 {Black recaptures the pawn and centralises the queen. In this chapter we will take a look at the alternatives to White's most natural move Nc3 , which is covered in the chapter The Main Line with Nc3 .} 3. Nf3 ({The development of the king's knight is the main alternative to} 3. Nc3 {. The idea behind the move is not to block the path of the c2 -pawn, so White can play c4 , which in combination with d4 will give them more pawn presence in the centre. There are a few alternatives worth mentioning.}) 3... c6 ({Black plays the move ... c6 as they regularly do in the Scandinavian Defence. The idea is to start the construction of 'the saw' by placing a pawn on c6 , followed by development of the bishop to g4 (in view of the early development of the white knight to f3 the development of the bishop on g4 is more active as it pins the knight) followed by ... e6 . With this being said, it's possible to start by changing the move order with} 3... Bg4 4. Be2 c6 {, which would lead to the same position as after c6} 5. d4 {Bg4 . Here it's time to fulfill the promise given in the Introduction and show the most famous game played in the Scandinavian Defence between Bill Gates and Magnus Carlsen. In this position, Black played Nc6 , though this position was reached via a different move order. White continued with Nc3 , attacking the queen on d5 , and Carlsen escaped to h5 , instead of our usual d8 . After} Qh5 {Black is hoping for a quick attack on White's kingside. Carlsen did this because he only had 30 seconds to finish the game, so he was clearly hoping for a quick win by a trick. Lo and behold, it worked like a charm! Gates played} 6. Bd3 {(a silly move really, blocking the advance of the d-pawn) and Carlsen played a sensible move} Nf6 {, developing the knight. White castled} 7. O-O {and Carlsen immediately pinned the knight on f3 with Bg4 . Gates chased away the bishop with h3 and here comes Carlsen's trick: Ne5!? It's a trap, into which Gates falls: He captured the sacrificed bishop with hxg4 Nfxg4 , but now he made the fatal mistake. He thought he could capture the knight on e5 with Nxe5?? , but what followed was the blue screen of death with} Qxh2+ {. If one of the richest people on the planet can be annihalated in mere 9 moves in the Scandinavian, surely we can all hope for something similar in our games?}) 4. d4 ({White expands in the centre. It's possible to change the plan and play} 4. Nc3 {when after} Qd8 5. d4 {play will transpose to the chapter The Main Line with Nc3 , analysed via the move order Nc3 Qd8 d4 c6 Nf3 .}) 4... Bg4 ({Black pins the knight on f3 and uses the fact that the queen is still on d5 , creating the threat ... Bxf3 , which would wreck White's kingside pawn structure as it would force White to recapture gxf3 , either immediately, or after the exchange of queens, leaving their whole kingside flank in ruins with doubled f-pawns and an isolated pawn on h2 . This move is more aggressive than the alternative} 4... Bf5 {, which is also possible.}) 5. Be2 {White breaks the pin and prevents the wrecking of the kingside pawn structure described in the previous comment.} e6 {Black successfully established 'the saw'. Once set, this pawn structure guarantees Black's safety, solidity and time to finish the development of the other light pieces.} 6. c4 ({This was White's idea that we talked about, to establish a central pawn duo on d4 and c4 . Again playing} 6. Nc3 Qd8 {will lead to similar positions examined in the chapter The Main Line with Nc3 with the slight difference that the light-squared bishop is on g4 instead of f5 . This difference doesn't affect Black's plans in the slightest (they are described in detail at the end of that chapter) and it is a testament of the fundamental soundness of the Scandinavian Defence: It doesn't depend on precise move orders (for example like many sharp lines of the Sicilian Defence) and it can be played with some flexibility.}) 6... Qd8 {The queen drops back home to the safest square.} 7. Nc3 {White develops the queen's knight.} Nf6 {Black develops the kingside first as they want to have the option to castle as soon as possible. The short castle will take care of the king's safety as it will provide a safe haven, far from the centre and a possible attack. Black's next moves will be ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 .} 8. O-O {White castles and plays natural, developing moves.} Be7 {It's useful to develop the bishop before the knight on b8 in order to have the option to castle in any moment. Now Black is ready to castle at the slightest hint of danger, which in this position could arise from the central advance d5 , potentially opening the central files.} 9. h3 {White can play this move at any moment and it's important to know that Black's usual reaction is to retreat the bishop to h5 .} Bh5 {The bishop exerts some pressure on White's position by keeping an eye on the knight on f3 . From h5 it can also drop back to g6 , for example if Black wants to exchange White's light-squared bishop on the d3 -square, or if it can attack targets on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Be3 {This is a sensible developing move that lends extra support to the d4 -pawn.} O-O *

