n Line with Nc3 with the slight difference that the light-squared bishop is on g4 instead of f5 . This difference doesn't affect Black's plans in the slightest (they are described in detail at the end of that chapter) and it is a testament of the fundamental soundness of the Scandinavian Defence: It doesn't depend on precise move orders (for example like many sharp lines of the Sicilian Defence) and it can be played with some flexibility.}) 6... Qd8 {The queen drops back home to the safest square.} 7. Nc3 {White develops the queen's knight.} Nf6 {Black develops the kingside first as they want to have the option to castle as soon as possible. The short castle will take care of the king's safety as it will provide a safe haven, far from the centre and a possible attack. Black's next moves will be ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 .} 8. O-O {White castles and plays natural, developing moves.} Be7 {It's useful to develop the bishop before the knight on b8 in order to have the option to castle in any moment. Now Black is ready to castle at the slightest hint of danger, which in this position could arise from the central advance d5 , potentially opening the central files.} 9. h3 {White can play this move at any moment and it's important to know that Black's usual reaction is to retreat the bishop to h5 .} Bh5 {The bishop exerts some pressure on White's position by keeping an eye on the knight on f3 . From h5 it can also drop back to g6 , for example if Black wants to exchange White's light-squared bishop on the d3 -square, or if it can attack targets on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Bg5 {The development of the bishop to g5 is a bit more aggressive than its development to e3 , but Black's position is so solid that they barely notice it.} O-O {After castling short nothing can stop Black from continuing with ... Nbd7 and establishing the desired opening arrangement of pieces.} *

