n Line with Nc3 with the slight difference that the light-squared bishop is on g4 instead of f5 . This difference doesn't affect Black's plans in the slightest (they are described in detail at the end of that chapter) and it is a testament of the fundamental soundness of the Scandinavian Defence: It doesn't depend on precise move orders (for example like many sharp lines of the Sicilian Defence) and it can be played with some flexibility.}) 6... Qd8 {The queen drops back home to the safest square.} 7. Nc3 {White develops the queen's knight.} Nf6 {Black develops the kingside first as they want to have the option to castle as soon as possible. The short castle will take care of the king's safety as it will provide a safe haven, far from the centre and a possible attack. Black's next moves will be ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 .} 8. O-O {White castles and plays natural, developing moves.} Be7 {It's useful to develop the bishop before the knight on b8 in order to have the option to castle in any moment. Now Black is ready to castle at the slightest hint of danger, which in this position could arise from the central advance d5 , potentially opening the central files.} 9. h3 {White can play this move at any moment and it's important to know that Black's usual reaction is to retreat the bishop to h5 .} Bh5 {The bishop exerts some pressure on White's position by keeping an eye on the knight on f3 . From h5 it can also drop back to g6 , for example if Black wants to exchange White's light-squared bishop on the d3 -square, or if it can attack targets on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Ne5 {The knight jump in the centre opens the d1 - h5 diagonal and now the bishop on e2 and the queen on d1 attack the black bishop on h5 . In such situations, Black gladly exchanges the light-squared bishops.} Bxe2 {Generally speaking, the exchange of the light-squared bishops works well for Black in the Scandinavian Defence.} 11. Nxe2 ({This is forced because the alternative recapture loses a pawn to} 11. Qxe2 $2 Qxd4 {. Now the pawn on d4 is safely guarded.}) 11... Nbd7 {Black completes development and immediately challenges White's centralised knight, which they would like to exchange. It's fine to postpone castling in this position because all White's pieces are very far from Black's position, which means that there is no immediate danger for Black to be aware of.} *

