n Line with Nc3 with the slight difference that the light-squared bishop is on g4 instead of f5 . This difference doesn't affect Black's plans in the slightest (they are described in detail at the end of that chapter) and it is a testament of the fundamental soundness of the Scandinavian Defence: It doesn't depend on precise move orders (for example like many sharp lines of the Sicilian Defence) and it can be played with some flexibility.}) 6... Qd8 {The queen drops back home to the safest square.} 7. Nc3 {White develops the queen's knight.} Nf6 {Black develops the kingside first as they want to have the option to castle as soon as possible. The short castle will take care of the king's safety as it will provide a safe haven, far from the centre and a possible attack. Black's next moves will be ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 .} 8. O-O {White castles and plays natural, developing moves.} Be7 {It's useful to develop the bishop before the knight on b8 in order to have the option to castle in any moment. Now Black is ready to castle at the slightest hint of danger, which in this position could arise from the central advance d5 , potentially opening the central files.} 9. h3 {White can play this move at any moment and it's important to know that Black's usual reaction is to retreat the bishop to h5 .} Bh5 {The bishop exerts some pressure on White's position by keeping an eye on the knight on f3 . From h5 it can also drop back to g6 , for example if Black wants to exchange White's light-squared bishop on the d3 -square, or if it can attack targets on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Re1 ({White places the rook on the semi-open e-file and here we see the usefulness of the option to be able to castle as Black can do it immediately. Other moves are possible, but they won't affect Black's play, for example,} 10. Be3 O-O {or} 11. Bg5 {O-O followed up with ... Nbd7 in both cases.}) ({Note that the knight jumps} 10. Ne5 {is met by} Bxe2 {and if White doesn't want to lose a pawn after} 11. Qxe2 Qxd4 {, the alternative is Nxe2 , after which Black continues with Nbd7 , challenging the knight on e5 .}) 10... O-O ({Black gets the king to safety. The hint for this move is the rook's appearance on the same file as the black king. This is finely illustrated in the case of} 10... Nbd7 $6 11. d5 $1 {when the black king becomes vulnerable on the e-file once the game is opened.}) 11. Bf4 {White can also develop the bishop to e3 or g5 , but this won't alter Black's next move or plans.} Nbd7 {Black completed the development and obtained the desired set-up. Before outlining Black's plans, it's important to know that generally, as a rule of thumb, Black is fine with exchanging their light-squared bishop either for a knight or a bishop. This means that Black shouldn't worry about the exchange of this piece at all.  Now onto Black's plans. They will revolve around the following ideas, some of which can be combined, depending on circumstances:  1. To push c5 , while being careful whether White's d5 -break is good or not.  2. To push the a-pawn by ... a5 - a4 - a3 , gaining space on the queenside and especially with a-pawn on a3 , intending to weaken White's queenside structure either by forcing the exchange bxa3 Rxa3 , which would leave White's a2 -pawn isolated on the a-file, or by b3 , which would leave Black with a far-advanced pawn on a3 and an excellent square on b4 , available for either a knight or a bishop. If White stops the advance of the a-pawn by playing a3 , that would lead to the weakening of the b3 -square and creation of a backward pawn on b2 .  3. To prepare the positional break b5 , fighting for control over the d5 -square. Then irrelevant of White's reaction: cxb5 , c5 or leaving Black to take ... bxc4 , Black will obtain the untouchable square d5 for a piece (most likely a knight).  4. To play the move ... Qa5 in order to connect the rooks, which will come to e8 , d8 , or c8 , depending on circumstances.  5. The pin ... Bb4 can sometimes create the threat of ... Bxc3 , which would inflict damage to White's queenside pawn structure if White is forced to recapture with a pawn.} ({A sample line of how the game could continue is Qd2} 11... Bb4 {, it makes sense to pin the knight on c3 with both the queen on d2 and the rook on e1 lined up on the same diagonal. After} 12. a3 Ba5 {, maintaining the pin and provoking White into expanding on the queenside, so} 13. b4 Bc7 {generally speaking, the side with less space, in this case Black, seeks exchanges of pieces. With fewer pieces, the remaining pieces have more room to maneuver effectively. The next moves,} 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 {Rad1 Bxf3 , still follow the outlined idea of exchanges of pieces Bxf3 Nb6 , targeting the c4 -pawn and luring White to advance with c5 , in which case Black will have obtained one of the main strategic aims - control of the d5 -square. After} 15. c5 $6 {Nc8! followed by ... Ne7 and ... Rfd8 , Black will ensure they always have a piece on d5 and not a pawn.}) *

