{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. Bb5+ {May look tempting to give a check, but this is just a waste of time. It forces Black to make the move they would have made anyway.} c6 {Of course, Black covers the check with a move that is part of their plan - the pawn on c6 is one of the pillars of 'the saw,' the other one being the pawn on e6 . When White removes the bishop from the attacked square Black will proceed with ... Bf5 and ... e6 to set-up 'the saw' and later develop with ... Nf6 , ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 .} *

