{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. g3 {The fianchetto of the bishop on g2 is a sensible development system, though not very efficient in this situation. The reason for this is that Black plays the move c6 anyway, and now the pawn pair on c6 and b7 has the added benefit of blunting the fianchettoed bishop on g2 .} c6 ({Black immediately establishes the limiting factor on the long diagonal. The best part is that the move} 4... c6 {is part of Black's plan anyway.}) 5. Bg2 {White continues with the intended development, but it is clear that the bishop won't be very active looking at the well-protected pawn on c6 .} Nf6 ({Since White is not applying any pressure in the centre, Black can develop at peace. It's also possible to start with} 5... Bf5 {. The development of the knight offers more flexibility as it keeps the option to develop the light-squared bishop to g4 as well as f5 .}) 6. Nf3 ({White prepares castling. In case of} 6. d4 Bf5 {(or Bg4 ) followed by ... e6 , ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 Black achieves the desired opening set-up.}) 6... Bf5 {The usual development of the bishop, though it's perfectly possible to develop it to g4 , too. In both cases, Black continues with ... e6 , ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 when the plans for this position are outlined at the end of this chapter.} *

