{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. Nf3 {White can start with development of the knight. Now it's important to play the following move.} Bf5 ({The reason for this move is that with a knight on f3 White created a threat of Bc4 and Ne5 / Ng5 , which would force the move ... e6 . Since Black doesn't want to be stuck with a bishop on c8 after ... e6 , they should develop the bishop immediately. As an illustration, if Black starts with} 4... c6 {, then after} 5. Bc4 Bf5 6. g4 {the bishop is exposed as} Bxg4 7. Ne5 $1 Bxd1 8. Bxf7# {leads to a mate Black would rather avoid.}) 5. Bc4 ({White plays for quick development and threatens Ne5 and/or g4 . Luckily, with the bishop already developed, Black is just in time to shut the a2 - g8 diagonal. Note that after} 5. d4 e6 {Black is safe and continues with ... c6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 , ... O-O and ... Nbd7 .}) 5... e6 {Black is safe now as the bishop on c4 has been blunted. Now Black can continue with the development with ... Nf6 , ... Be7 , and ... O-O , postponing the move ... c6 as the development of the kingside takes precedence. In addition to this, if White postpones the advance of their d-pawn, Black may consider playing ... c5 and ... Nc6 , establishing control of the d4 -square.} *

