{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. Bc4 ({An active development of the bishop, which we also saw in the line starting with} 4. Nf3 {. The importance of this line lies in the fact that it's the only exception in the whole repertoire when it comes to Black's development.}) 4... c5 ({To understand why Black plays differently here, it's useful to compare this line with the one starting with knight's development Nf3 . In both cases White wants to play Bc4 and Nf3 and create a threat against the pawn on f7 . In the line with Nf3 the f3 -square is occupied by a knight, so Black could play ... Bf5 and ... e6 to blunt the diagonal for the white light-squared bishop. However, in this position the f3 -square is vacant. This means that in the case of} 4... Bf5 {,} 5. Qf3 $1 {is a very powerful double attack on the bishop on f5 and the pawn on b7 . The only move to defend both is} Qc8 {, but after} 6. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 7. g4 {White has a serious attack against Black's uncastled king. On the other hand, without a knight on f3 White has less control over the central d4 -square. With these two reasons put together, we arrive at Black's best move,} c5 {Black obtains control over the d4 -square and wants to develop with ... Nc6 and clamp White down in the centre by preventing the liberating d4 -advance. If Black is forced to play ... e6 with a bishop on c8 , in order to blunt the white bishop on c4 , the bishop on c8 will conveniently be developed after ... b6 and ... Bb7 , with excellent prospects on the long diagonal.}) 5. Nf3 ({White fights for control of the d4 -square and threatens the advance d4 . In the case of} 5. Qf3 {(threatening Qxf7 )} e6 6. Nge2 Nc6 {Black establishes control over the d4-square and develops with ... Nf6 , ... Be7 , and ... O-O , when at a later stage the jump ... Nd4 and the centralisation with ... Nd5 will be Black's main ideas.}) 5... Nc6 {Black reasserts control over the d4 -square and prevents White's advance.} 6. O-O ({The primitive} 6. Ng5 $2 {is met by} e6 {and with the knight on g5 being attacked by the queen on d8 , White only managed to waste time. It's easy to get carried away with White and lose quickly after} 7. Qh5 $2 {(threatening Qxf7 mate)} g6 8. Qg4 Nh6 {and White loses the knight on g5 as the queen cannot defend it for much longer after} 9. Qf4 Bd6 10. Qe3 Nf5 {and Black wins the knight on g5 on the next move with ... Qxg5 .}) 6... Nf6 {Black continues the development of the kingside.} 7. d3 {White must open the c1 - h6 diagonal for the bishop on c1 .} Bg4 {This is the move most in the spirit of the Scandinavian Defence. Black develops the bishop by pinning the knight on f3 before playing ... e6 .} 8. h3 ({White would like to get rid of the bishop. Note that the sacrifice} 8. Bxf7+ $2 Kxf7 {only loses a piece as} 9. Ne5+ {doesn't win back the bishop because after} Nxe5 {White loses another.}) 8... Bxf3 ({In this situation the capture is the only good option. Retreating to h5 , which is usually a good alternative, doesn't work here in view of} 8... Bh5 $6 9. Bb5 $1 {followed by g4 and Ne5 , with pressure on the pinned knight on c6 .}) 9. Qxf3 e6 {Black can finish development at peace. After ... Be7 and ... O-O Black can also play ... Rc8 (this is especially useful if White pins the knight on c6 by Bb5 ), though the main threat will be ... Nd4 , centralising the knight and attacking both the queen on f3 and the pawn on c2 .} *

