{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Bc4 {With the development of the bishop on c4 White wants to target the f7 -pawn.} Bf5 {Black develops the light-squared bishop and intends ... e6 , to set-up 'the saw' and blunt the bishop on c4 .} 6. Bxf7+ {This is another very rare attempt. I show it so that it doesn't affect you with its surprise value.} Kxf7 {Black takes the bishop.} 7. Qf3 {This is White's idea. By pinning the bishop on f5 , White will regain the piece.} ({Note that giving a check on h5 loses on the spot, as} 7. Qh5+ $2 g6 {defends against the check and at the same time defends the bishop on f5 . Black simply remains a piece up.}) ({Similarly bad is} 7. Nf3 $2 Nf6 {, when the black king can be tucked away to g8 and White has nothing to show for the lost piece.}) 7... e6 {Black develops the bishop and opens the diagonals for the dark-squared bishop and the queen.} 8. g4 {White attacks the pinned bishop.} Qf6 ({By placing the queen between the king and the opponent's queen Black breaks the pin on the bishop on f5 and now threatens to remove the bishop from the attacked square and remain a piece up. An alternative is the pawn-grabbing} 8... Qxd4 {, when Black will be a pawn up after} 9. gxf5 Qe5+ {followed by ... Qxf5 . Now White must take the bishop if they don't want to be lost immediately.}) 9. gxf5 Qxf5 {Black recaptures the pawn and seeks an exchange of queens. Black plans to finish development with ... Nf6 , ... Nbd7 and ... Be7 , after which the artificial castling by ... Rhf8 and ... Kg8 can be completed.} *

