{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Bc4 {With the development of the bishop on c4 White wants to target the f7 -pawn.} Bf5 {Black develops the light-squared bishop and intends ... e6 , to set-up 'the saw' and blunt the bishop on c4 .} 6. Bf4 {This is a developing move for White, but one that doesn't affect Black's plans.} e6 {Black continues with the plan. After the pawn move Black will play ... Nf6 , ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 , achieving the desired opening set-up.} *

