{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Bc4 {With the development of the bishop on c4 White wants to target the f7 -pawn.} Bf5 {Black develops the light-squared bishop and intends ... e6 , to set-up 'the saw' and blunt the bishop on c4 .} 6. g4 ({An aggressive idea for White that Black should know about, though it's not a move that is frequent in practice. By far the most natural and common move in this position is} 6. Nf3 {, which would transpose to the lines after Nf3 .}) 6... Bg6 {The bishop retreats. Black's plan remains unchanged: ... e6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 (or in this case even ... Bb4 - the idea is to pin the knight on c3 and obtain access to the e4 -square for the bishop transfer ... Be4 - d5 , thus escaping a possible attack with h4 - h5 ) and ... Nbd7 .} 7. f4 {Threatens to trap the bishop with f5 .} e6 {Black plays the planned move that stops f5 and threatens the check ... Qh4 at the same time. If allowed, that check would cause serious discomfort to the white king.} 8. Nf3 {White develops and controls the h4 -square, thus preventing the check from h4 .} Nf6 {Black continues with development and attacks the pawn on g4 .} 9. Rg1 {White defends the pawn with the rook.} Bb4 {The key move for Black in these positions. The bishop pins the knight on c3 and by doing so it allows Black access to the e4 -square. This square can be used for the escape maneuver ... Be4 - d5 (as White may threatens f5 to trap the bishop), seeking the exchange of the light-squared bishops. Additionally, the pin can also be used to attack the knight on c3 with ... Ne4 or ... Nd5 . These ideas give Black counterplay in the centre.} *

