{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Bc4 {With the development of the bishop on c4 White wants to target the f7 -pawn.} Bf5 {Black develops the light-squared bishop and intends ... e6 , to set-up 'the saw' and blunt the bishop on c4 .} 6. g4 ({An aggressive idea for White that Black should know about, though it's not a move that is frequent in practice. By far the most natural and common move in this position is} 6. Nf3 {, which would transpose to the lines after Nf3 .}) 6... Bg6 {The bishop retreats. Black's plan remains unchanged: ... e6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 (or in this case even ... Bb4 - the idea is to pin the knight on c3 and obtain access to the e4 -square for the bishop transfer ... Be4 - d5 , thus escaping a possible attack with h4 - h5 ) and ... Nbd7 .} 7. Nge2 ({The move} 7. h4 {is met by} h5 $1 {and Black stabilises the kingside after} 8. g5 e6 {. By developing the knight White intends Nf4 and h4 - h5 , harassing the bishop on g6 .}) 7... e6 {Black establishe 'the saw' and is ready to continue with development.} 8. h4 ({White wants to trap the bishop with h5 . In the case of} 8. Nf4 Bb4 $1 {again is the move to remember, pinning the knight and obtaining access to the e4 -square, similar to the line after} 9. h4 {.}) 8... Bb4 {This is an important move for Black that is essential in the sharp lines where White tries to attack quickly on the kingside. The idea is to pin the knight on c3 in order to allow the bishop on g6 to escape via the e4 -square, thus the manoeuvre ... Be4 - d5 becomes possible.  Once on d5 , the bishop doesn't mind being exchanged as that would strengthen Black's central pawn presence after ... cxd5 . The position is sharp, but Black's inherent solidity hasn't been affected and the development with ... Nd7 (or ... Nc6 if the exchange on d5 has happened), ... Ne7 (this is preferable to ... Nf6 , which can be attacked by g5 ) and then ... Qc7 or ... Qa5 with the king being flexible as queenside castling is possible. These ideas give Black a harmonious development. I will stress again, this is not a line you will often meet in practice, but it's important to know how to react if White plays in ultra-aggressive manner and how to absorb that early pressure and still obtain good development.} *

