{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Nf3 {This move is the most commonly played, but it allows Black smooth development.} Bf5 ({This is the standard development, preparing 'the saw' with ... e6 , though in this situation the pin with} 5... Bg4 {is also possible.}) 6. Bf4 {The development of the dark-squared bishop is possible, but again doesn't bother Black.} e6 {Black establishes 'the saw' and will continue with ... Be7 , ... O-O , and ... Nbd7 , with a successful opening deployment.} *

