{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Nf3 {This move is the most commonly played, but it allows Black smooth development.} Bf5 ({This is the standard development, preparing 'the saw' with ... e6 , though in this situation the pin with} 5... Bg4 {is also possible.}) 6. Nh4 {A concrete move, attacking the bishop on f5 .} Bg6 {The bishop drops back to a protected square. Black follows the general rule of thumb... The exchange of the light-squared bishop is acceptable.} 7. Nxg6 {The exchange of knight for bishop was White's idea, but Black recaptures with the h-pawn and opens the h-file.} hxg6 {Black recaptures toward the centre and opens the h-file. The next development will follow the usual pattern of ... e6 and ... Nf6 when Black will have a choice: To continue with ... Be7 , ... O-O and ... Nbd7 , or to show more aggressive intentions thanks to the open h-file and play ... Bd6 , ... Nbd7 and ... Qc7 , perhaps followed up with ... O-O-O with ideas to attack on the kingside.} *

