{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Nf3 {This move is the most commonly played, but it allows Black smooth development.} Bf5 ({This is the standard development, preparing 'the saw' with ... e6 , though in this situation the pin with} 5... Bg4 {is also possible.}) 6. Bc4 {An active development of the bishop, though it will be blunted after Black's next move. White has several alternatives.} e6 {'The saw' is in place. It is the basis of Black's position and it allows for comfortable development behind the safety of the solid pawn structure.} 7. O-O ({In the case of} 7. Ne5 Nd7 {Black immediately challenges the knight on e5 .}) 7... Nf6 {Black develops with the most natural moves. First the kingside is developed, to allow for a quick castle.} 8. Re1 {White also develops naturally. The rook will inevitably come to e1 as it's the best square for it.} Be7 {With the king being a bit sensitive on the e-file after White's last move, it makes sense for Black to develop the bishop on e7 and allow for a quick castling.} 9. Nh4 {White goes after the bishop. We saw this idea on the previous move as well. Black's reaction is the same, to escape with the bishop to g6 .} Bg6 {Now the exchange on g6 improves Black's pawn structure.} 10. Nxg6 hxg6 ({This recapture towards the centre opens the h-file and strengthens Black's kingside structure, making it more robust. With the bishop already on e7 (rather than on d6 , as mentioned as a possibility in the comment to the line Nh4 Bg6 Nxg6} 10... hxg6 {) Black will likely castle short and play ... Nbd7 , though they may still entertain the thought of castling long and using the h-file for more aggressive ideas.}) *

