{This chapter analyses the main line in the course as it deals with White's strongest and most natural plan of capturing on d5 , followed up by the attack on the queen on d5 with Nc3 .} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White's most natural move, developing the knight and attacking the queen on d5 .} Qd8 {The queen returns home to the safest spot. Black will now continue with development ... c6 , ... Bf5 and ... e6 , to set up 'the saw' - the black pawns on c6 and e6 with the light-squared bishop active on f5 . There are certain details when it comes to the move order of achieving 'the saw' so these should be carefully taken into consideration.} 4. d4 {Again the most natural move for White, taking up central space.} c6 {Black prepares 'the saw' by controlling the d5 -square with the pawn on c6 . Next the bishop will be developed to f5 after which 'the saw' will be complete after ... e6 .} 5. Nf3 {This move is the most commonly played, but it allows Black smooth development.} Bf5 ({This is the standard development, preparing 'the saw' with ... e6 , though in this situation the pin with} 5... Bg4 {is also possible.}) 6. Bc4 {An active development of the bishop, though it will be blunted after Black's next move. White has several alternatives.} e6 {'The saw' is in place. It is the basis of Black's position and it allows for comfortable development behind the safety of the solid pawn structure.} 7. O-O ({In the case of} 7. Ne5 Nd7 {Black immediately challenges the knight on e5 .}) 7... Nf6 {Black develops with the most natural moves. First the kingside is developed, to allow for a quick castle.} 8. Re1 {White also develops naturally. The rook will inevitably come to e1 as it's the best square for it.} Be7 {With the king being a bit sensitive on the e-file after White's last move, it makes sense for Black to develop the bishop on e7 and allow for a quick castling.} 9. Bf4 {White completes development.} Nbd7 {It's possible to castle first, but since there is no immediate danger to the black king it's also possible to complete the development of the light pieces, at the same time controlling the e5 -square.} 10. Qd2 ({If White jumps to e5 Black gladly exchanges the knight after} 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O {, with a very solid position, when the same plans described below apply.}) 10... O-O {Black has reached the ideal set-up. This marks the end of the opening and the start of the middlegame. It is very important to know how to continue from here and what options Black has at their disposal. This knowledge will give you confidence so you will never feel at a loss and suffer a lack of ideas in the middlegame. The following is the list of possible plans and ideas:  1. To push ... c5 while being careful that the opening of the position after either dxc5 or d5 is acceptable.  2. To play ... Nd5 looking for exchanges. If white takes Nxd5 then Black takes with the c6 -pawn and starts a minority attack on the queenside.  3. To gain space on the queenside by ... a5 - a4 - a3 .  4. To play ... Qa5 in order to connect the rooks, which will come to e8 , d8 or c8 , depending on circumstances.} ({With these plans and ideas outlined, what follows is a sample line that shows how easily White can end up in trouble by playing seemingly natural moves: Rad1} 10... Nd5 11. Bg3 $6 {it's better to take on d5 but that is also good for Black after Nxd5 cxd5} Bd3 12. Bxd3 {Qxd3} Rc8 {when Black can start planning the minority attack on the queenside by pushing the a and b-pawns forward. Bb4} 13. h3 {White seems perfectly positioned but without a clear plan of what to do next. This is the main 'trap' Black aims for when playing the Scandinavian - 'natural' play will lead White nowhere.} Qa5 {there is already insufferable pressure on the knight on c3 , so White must relinquish the bishop pair Bxd5 cxd5 and we have reached a position where Black is much better as it's possible to increase the pressure on the c-file and the e1 - a5 diagonal by putting a rook on the c8 -square.}) *

