1. e4 d5 2. Nf3 dxe4 3. Ng5 Bf5 {Nakamura defends the pawn on f5 as recommended in the theoretical chapter.} 4. Nc3 {White attacks the pawn one more time.} Nf6 {Black also defends the pawn for the second time. Observe how difficult it is for White to regain the lost pawn.} 5. Bc4 {White attacks the pawn on f7 .} e6 {Black erects a barrier on the path of the light-squared bishop.} 6. Qe2 {White attacks the pawn on d4 for a third time.} Nc6 ({A tactical defence of the pawn on d4 by Nakamura. It was possible to defend it simply by} 6... Qd4 {.}) 7. Bb5 ({The justification of Nakamura's move is seen after} 7. Ngxe4 Nd4 8. Qd3 Bc5 {and White can barely move. Castling loses after} 9. O-O Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Qh4 {(attacking the pinned knight on e4 )} 11. f3 Nxf3+ 12. Kh1 Qxh2# {.}) 7... Qd4 {Defending the pawn for a third time. White cannot attack it one more time and given the dominating position of that pawn decides to exchange it, thus remaining a pawn down.} 8. d3 exd3 9. cxd3 Qd7 {Black is a clear pawn up with absolutely no compensation for White. The rest is easy for Nakamura.} 10. Be3 a6 {Getting rid of the pin on the knight.} 11. Bxc6 Qxc6 12. O-O Be7 {Black simply finishes the development and wants to castle short.} 13. Rac1 Qd7 {The queen steps aside from possible discovered attacks along the c-file.} 14. Nce4 O-O {Development completed.} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Ne4 Be7 {Black preserves the pair of bishops.} 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 {The pawn on d3 is isolated and weak, as it cannot be defended by another pawn.} 18. Bc5 {White manages to exchange one black bishop, but that doesn't help him much.} b6 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. d4 Bxe4 {The simplest. Without any minor pieces, Black will be able to use his queen and two rooks to attack the lone pawn on d4 .} 21. Qxe4 Rd5 {The plan is to triple on the d-file and attack the pawn on d4 .} 22. Qf4 {White counterattacks the pawn on c7 , but this is easily dealt with.} Rc8 {Black simply defends the pawn.} 23. h3 Qd7 {Now the attack on the pawn on d4 starts. The threat is to use the c-pawn in the attack by playing ... c5 , using the fact that White cannot take on c5 with his pawn as then the rook on d1 would be lost.} 24. Qg4 {White defends the rook, but now the rook from c8 can join the attack.} Rd8 {Attacking the pawn for a third time. The fourth time will be with the move ... c5 , which would lead to the capture of the d4 -pawn.} 25. Qg3 c5 {Four attacks is too many. White cannot take on c5 since Black wins the rook on d1: dxc5? Rxd1 .} 26. Qa3 a5 {Nakamura doesn't allow the slightest consolation, not giving up on any of his pawns.} 27. Qb3 b5 {The same principle.} 28. a4 {Desperation, but White is lost anyway.} bxa4 {Now it's harvest time.} 29. Qb6 cxd4 {Three pawns up.} 30. Rc7 Qd6 31. Qb7 Rf8 {Just defending against Rxf7 , when the passed d-pawn will decide.} 32. Rdc1 d3 *

