1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 c6 4. Nf3 Nf6 ({Black starts with} 4... Nf6 {, which is also possible.}) 5. Be3 {A possible development for White, though not very challenging.} Bg4 {Now the bishop comes out to g4 before 'the saw' comes into existence.} 6. Nbd2 e6 {'The saw' is established and Black already has a good position.} 7. h3 Bh5 {Keeping the pin on the knight on f3 is a standard reaction for Black.} 8. Be2 {White breaks the pin.} Nbd7 {A characteristic moment. Since White didn't play c4 to chase the centralised queen away, Black modified the plans slightly - he doesn't want to wait for c4 and continues development, correctly judging that in the case of c4 , the queen will also be fine on a5 .} 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. c4 Qa5 ({Here it comes, the queen is also fine on a5 . After all, that is one of Black's ideas after the opening, to play} 11... Qa5 {and connect the rooks.}) 12. Qb3 {Targeting the pawn on b7 .} Qc7 {The queen drops back to defend the pawn on b7 .} 13. Rac1 Rfe8 {As explained in the theoretical chapter, the rooks can occupy the e8 , d8 , and c8 squares.} 14. Bd3 Bg6 {A typical reaction based on the fact that the exchange of the light-squared bishops is usually in Black's favour.} 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Bg5 Rad8 {Black is fully centralised with a bullet-proof position.} 17. Ne5 {A common idea, but Black is ready for it.} Nxe5 {Black exchanges the centralised knight.} 18. dxe5 Nd7 {The d5 -square is not available, so the knight drops to d7 and eyes the c5 and d3 squares.} 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Nf3 {A blunder, missing Black's idea.} Nc5 {A double attack. When the queen moves, the knight lands on d3 , forking both rooks.} 21. Qe3 Nd3 {Black wins an exchange, so White resigns.} *

