1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 ({In the theoretical chapter the recommended move order is} 4... c6 {, but this is perfectly possible.}) 5. Bf4 c6 6. Qd2 {White plans to castle long.} Bf5 {Black follows the recommended development.} 7. O-O-O e6 {'The saw' is in place.} 8. Nf3 Bb4 {Active development of the bishop, motivated by White's long castle. Black starts active play against the white king.} 9. Nh4 {White goes after the active bishop on f5 , but underestimates Black's swift counterplay.} Ne4 ({A counterattack on the queen on d2 , the knight on c3 , and the knight on h4 . However, it was better to start with the capture on c3 first,} 9... Bxc3 10. Qxc3 Ne4 {followed by ... Qxh4 .}) 10. Qe3 {White unpins and attacks the knight on e4 .} Nxc3 11. bxc3 {The decisive mistake. It was better for White to take the bishop on f5 and sacrifice the rook on d1 .} Ba3+ 12. Kb1 ({A mistake leading to mate, but even in the case of the better} 12. Kd2 Qxh4 {Black is a piece up.}) 12... Qb6+ 13. Ka1 Qb2# *

