1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 c6 5. Bc4 Bf5 6. Be3 {A possible developing move. It doesn't affect Black's plans.} Nf6 7. Qe2 e6 {Black established 'the saw'.} 8. a3 Nbd7 {Since the e-file is blocked by the bishop on e3 and there is no immediate danger to Black's king, Black postpones the development of the bishop. As we shall see, he has an idea to develop the bishop into a more active square.} 9. Nf3 Bd6 {From d6 the bishop controls the e5 -square, thus preventing possible Ne5 . Note that this development was possible because White blocked the e-file with the move Be3 early on.} 10. Bg5 Qc7 {Black removes the queen from the pin. Now the knight on f6 is free to move. There is another, deeper, point to the queen move, explained in the next note.} 11. Bh4 ({The tactical justification of Black's play is seen in the line after} 11. d5 {(White wants to take advantage of the fact that the Black king is still uncastled and in the centre)} cxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxc2 {and Black wins a pawn - this was the point of playing the move Qc7 , so that after the opening of the c-file the queen could capture the pawn on c2 .}) 11... O-O {Black completes development.} 12. Bg3 Rad8 {Centralising the rook.} 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rd1 Nd5 {One of Black's standard ideas, the placement of a knight on the central d5 -square. There are two concrete ideas behind this move: to take on c3 , forcing bxc3 , which would lead to a win of a pawn by ... Qxa3 , and the jump ... Nf4 , which would embarrass the queen on e2 and the pawn on g2 . Notice how from this moment onwards Black's play is very forceful and concrete, creating threats with every move he makes.} 15. Ne4 {White avoids both threats by escaping with the knight with tempo, attacking the queen on d6 .} Qf4 {Black escapes with the queen and attacks the knight on e4 at the same time.} 16. Nfd2 Bg4 {The attack continues, in order not to lose material White must weaken his position.} 17. f3 {The only move to block the attack on the d1 - h5 diagonal, but now the e3 -square has been weakened.} Bf5 {The bishop retreats and creates the threat of ... Ne3 .} 18. g3 {White tries to get rid of the active queen.} Qh6 {The queen retreats to a square from where it still controls the e3 -square, thus renewing the threat of ... Ne3 .} 19. f4 {White blocks the c1 - h6 diagonal, thus stopping the queen's control of the e3 -square.} N7f6 {Black is persistent. The knight is en route to g4 , from where it will target the weak e3 -square.} 20. c3 Ng4 {One of the knights wants to land on e3 .} 21. Nf1 {White covers the e3 -square.} e5 {A beautiful move that opens the game with the white king still stuck in the centre.} 22. dxe5 {Taking with the other pawn opens the queen's access to the e3 -square, which Black will use to land a knight there.} Bxe4 {A pretty combination based on the tactical motif of the fork.} 23. Qxe4 Nxc3 24. Bxf7+ ({Black's idea is seen after} 24. bxc3 Rxd1+ 25. Kxd1 Nf2+ {forking the king on d1 and the queen on e4 , thus winning the queen.}) 24... Kxf7 {Black takes with the king to have the rook on f8 defend the rook on d8 .} 25. e6+ Kf6 {There was nothing wrong with putting the king back to g8 , but even on f6 the king is perfectly safe as White has no pieces to attack it.} 26. bxc3 Rxd1+ 27. Ke2 ({Taking the rook again leads to the fork} 27. Kxd1 Nf2+ {, winning the queen.}) 27... Qh5 {Preparing a deadly discovered check.} 28. e7 Re8 29. Qf3 ({White resigned, not waiting for one of the many winning moves, from the simple retreat Rd7 , which leaves Black a full rook up, to the more forcing Rxe7} 29. Kxd1 Nf2+ {, winning the queen on f3 .}) *

